udes only the artifact. For a new test driver, it could start with the current build.gradle. There seems to be a need for a deterministic dependency for the test scaffold to add swagger-annotations. The artifact claims swagger annotations are provided, so if we’re testing with model class annotations, I’ll need to include the specific test implementation dependency. Existing tests already have this. I'm wondering if this is necessary beyond the standard generated scaffold.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying test dependency needs**\\n\\nIt looks like my tests need an explicit `testImplementation` for `io.swagger.core.v3:swagger-annotations`, but the existing build already includes version 2.2.25. The Forge workflow raises the question of whether the library setup goes beyond the usual generated scaffold because the artifact's dependency won’t transitively bring in the annotations. To compile tests referencing `@Schema`, the explicit dependency is necessary. The `jsonschema-generator` is provided in the module POM, but the existing build adds it, leading me to wonder if the generator dependency is needed beyond what's normal.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Configuring module test setup**\\n\\nTo use the module for tests, I need to instantiate `SchemaGeneratorConfigBuilder` and `SchemaGenerator` from the generator. I wonder if I could cover `Swagger2Module.applyToConfigBuilder` with a mocked config, but real coverage needs the actual generator. Existing tests already have it, and the deterministic setup only includes entries. I can add dependencies, but I need to decide on concrete versions. For the generator, I’ll use version 5.0.0 with `testImplementation`. Should I consider adding a BOM as well? The deterministic entry schema doesn’t specify the platform; it’s just the group, artifact, and version.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating swagger compatibility**\\n\\nI need to figure out if swagger annotation version 2.2.25 works with 5.0.0. I think I should look at the POM parent for dependency management to see the version it uses. Maybe I should inspect the parent POM file to find the version details. I'll consider searching through the cached parent to check for any relevant information that could help clarify this compatibility issue. Let's see what it reveals!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_0tpQcpbPg0H9lZfLG8jRYB2q|fc_00459a980397370a016a404f6a579c8195b16013a4de242762", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.m2/repository/com/github/victools/jsonschema-generator-parent/5.0.0 ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/com.github.victools/jsonschema-generator-parent/5.0.0 -type f -name '*.pom' 2>/dev/null | head -5", "timeout": 30}}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_1cld1rahqxxYYpiYfrBpgc7q|fc_00459a980397370a016a404f6a57b48195806b28346d273c31", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python3 - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request\nurl='https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/com/github/victools/jsonschema-generator-parent/5.0.0/jsonschema-generator-parent-5.0.0.pom'\ntry:\n data=urllib.request.urlopen(url, timeout=20).read().decode()\n for needle in ['swagger-annotations', 'jackson-databind', 'classmate']:\n  i=data.find(needle)\n  print('---',needle, i)\n  print(data[max(0,i-300):i+500] if i>=0 else '')\nexcept Exception as e: print(type(e).__name__, e)\nPY", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2109, "output": 1354, "cacheRead": 24064, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 27527, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782599513293, "responseId": "resp_00459a980397370a016a404f59c67c819591594429252ab0b9"}}
